Vuyargur hungers for your help.<hex:02100103><hex:02100103>※Please note that the difficulty of this quest has been synced to your current level. Furthermore, you may not proceed with a class or job that is different from when you accepted this quest.
Speak with Garharlor.
Deliver the requested supplies to Vuyargur.
Speak with Garharlor.

Ah, <hex:022C0DFF07><hex:022903EB0203><hex:FF02> <hex:0203>, glad to─ <rumble>
Nnngh... Forgive my clamoring belly. Working in the cold, it seems I can scarcely digest a meal before I'm dreaming of the next.
Still, I know those doing the heavy lifting and shoveling must be even more ravenous.
The bitter cold has taken its toll on our stomachs, particularly those of us doing the lifting and shoveling.
To replenish our dwindling food stores, a new cornfield is to be tilled at the foot of the mountain, but we've been asked to furnish the supplies ourselves.
It is this task with which I would request your assistance, <hex:022C0DFF07><hex:022903EB0203><hex:FF02> <hex:0203>. Speak to Garharlor here, who shall provide you with everything you need.
Ah, <hex:022C0DFF07><hex:022903EB0203><hex:FF02> <hex:0203>, I hear you'll be assisting us with preparations for the cornfield.
I'd like you to build large, sturdy containers to hold compost. Should you run out of materials, I will gladly provide more.
I'd like you to craft some tools used in plowing the fields. Should you run out of materials, I will gladly provide more.
I'd like you to concoct growth formula for use on the crops. Should you run out of ingredients, I will gladly provide more.
Oh, and once you've finished, hand it all straight to Vuyargur─he will know what to do with it.
Have you run out of materials? ...Seems not. Carry on, then, and submit whatever you finish to Vuyargur.
Have you run out of materials? Use these, then.
Any progress on those field supplies?
Oh, these will be perfect! I'll make sure they're sent to the site straightaway.
And here's your reward for a job well─ <rumble>
...Ahem. I think it's time I went and found something to eat.
And while our meals as of late have been pleasantly filling, we may need more supplies sooner rather than later. All this hard labor really works up an appetite!
